revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=September 2014}} [[Image:Yorkshire sculpture park underground gallery.JPG|thumb|200px|A basic brise soleil at the Underground gallery at the [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]]. This photo was taken at noon in April, a little after the [[vernal equinox]]. Note how the top of the glazing is in shade. As the passage of summer continues, the noon shading on the glass will be greater.]] '''Brise soleil''', sometimes '''brise-soleil''' ({{IPA-fr|bʁiːz sɔlɛj}}, plural, "brise-soleil" (invariable), or "bris-ole", from [[French language|French]], "sun breaker"), is an [[Architecture|architectural]] feature of a building that reduces [[solar gain|heat gain]] within that building by deflecting sunlight.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Matter: Material Processes in Architectural Production|last = |first = |publisher = Routledge|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 330|editor-last = Peter Borden|editor-first = Gail|editor2-last = Meredith|editor2-first = Michael}}</ref>
==Architecture== Brise-soleils can comprise a variety of permanent [[sun shade|sun-shading]] structures, ranging from the simple patterned concrete walls popularized by [[Le Corbusier]] in the [[Palace of Assembly (Chandigarh)|Palace of Assembly]] to the elaborate wing-like mechanism devised by [[Santiago Calatrava]] for the [[Milwaukee Art Museum]] or the mechanical, pattern-creating devices of the [[Institut du Monde Arabe]] by [[Jean Nouvel]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
In the typical form, a horizontal projection extends from the sunside facade of a building. This is most commonly used to prevent facades with a large amount of glass from overheating during the summer. Often [[louver]]s are incorporated into the shade to prevent the high-angle summer sun falling on the facade, but also to allow the low-angle winter sun to provide some [[passive solar heating]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Dictionary of Construction Terms|last = Tolson|first = Simon|publisher = CRC Press|year = 2014|isbn = |location = |pages = 40|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JPVfAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA40&dq=brise%20soleil&pg=PA40#v=onepage&q=brise%20soleil&f=false}}</ref>
