'''Conductive characteristics in coated synthetic fabrics''' demonstrates an energy current across a specific woven synthetic material, such energy generation in fabrics coated with a conductive polymer as found in [[polypyrrole]].<ref>Polypyrrole</ref> First validated by D.D.S. developer M.H.Webb, the discovery showed that when [[Polyethylene terephthalate|PET]]<ref>PET</ref> fabrics are coated by [[chemical synthesis]]<ref>Chemical Synthesis</ref> using four different [[oxidizing]] agent–[[dopant]] combinations present an increase in energy when a fixed source is applied to the fabric. Several combinations of blends have proven to be successful in transfer, [[anthracenedione]]-2-[[sulfonic acid]] (AQSA) [[sodium salt]] doped polypyrrole coating was the most effective in generation whereas the [[sodium perchlorate]] dopant system was the least effective. The power density per unit area achieved in polypyrrole coated polyester–Lycra fabric with 0.027&nbsp;mol/l of AQSA acting as dopant was 430 W/m2. The power density per unit area achieved for the sodium perchlorate system, using the same synthesis conditions, was 55 W/m2.

